), Maldives (
<bibRefCitation author="Randall, JE" journalOrPublisher="Smith Institute of Ichthyology" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="1 - 47" refId="B24" refString="Randall, JE, Anderson, RC, 1993. Annotated checklist of the epipelagic and shore fishes of the Maldive Islands. Ichthyological Bulletin of the J. L. B. Smith Institute of Ichthyology 59: 1 - 47" title="Annotated checklist of the epipelagic and shore fishes of the Maldive Islands. Ichthyological Bulletin of the J. L. B." volume="59" year="1993">Randall and Anderson 1993</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Valenciennes" authorityYear="1840" class="Actinopterygii" family="Labridae" genus="Cheilinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cheilinus arenatus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Cheilinus arenatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, RC" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" refId="B1" refString="Anderson, RC, Randall, JE, Kuiter, RH, 1998. Additions to the fish fauna of the Maldive Islands. Part 2: New records of fishes from the Maldive Islands, with notes on other species. Ichthyological Bulletin of the J. L. B. Smith Institute of Ichthyology 67: 20-32, pls. 1-4." title="Additions to the fish fauna of the Maldive Islands. Part 2: New records of fishes from the Maldive Islands, with notes on other species. Ichthyological Bulletin of the J. L. B. Smith Institute of Ichthyology 67: 20 - 32, pls. 1 - 4." year="1998">Anderson et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
), Mozambique (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/MF01125" author="Gell, FR" journalOrPublisher="Marine and Freshwater Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="115 - 121" refId="B15" refString="Gell, FR, Whittington, MW, 2002. Diversity of fishes in seagrass beds in the Quirimba Archipelago, northern Mozambique. Marine and Freshwater Research 53 (2): 115 - 121, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1071/MF01125" title="Diversity of fishes in seagrass beds in the Quirimba Archipelago, northern Mozambique." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/MF01125" volume="53" year="2002">Gell and Whittington 2002</bibRefCitation>
), Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Randall, JE" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Studies (Taipei, Taiwan)" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="135 - 139" refId="B25" refString="Randall, JE, Khalaf, M, 2003. Redescription of the labrid fish Oxycheilinus orientalis (Guenther), a senior synonym of O. rhodochrous (Guenther), and the first record from the Red Sea. Zoological Studies (Taipei, Taiwan) 42 (1): 135 - 139" title="Redescription of the labrid fish Oxycheilinus orientalis (Guenther), a senior synonym of O. rhodochrous (Guenther), and the first record from the Red Sea." volume="42" year="2003">Randall and Khalaf 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4509.1.1" author="Golani, D" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="1 - 215" refId="B17" refString="Golani, D, Fricke, R, 2018. Checklist of the Red Sea fishes with delineation of the Gulf of Suez, Gulf of Aqaba, endemism and Lessepsian migrants. Zootaxa 4509 (1): 1 - 215, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4509.1.1" title="Checklist of the Red Sea fishes with delineation of the Gulf of Suez, Gulf of Aqaba, endemism and Lessepsian migrants." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4509.1.1" volume="4509" year="2018">Golani and Fricke 2018</bibRefCitation>
), Madagascar (
<bibRefCitation author="Fricke, R" journalOrPublisher="] Ichthy, Natural History of Fishes of Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" refId="B6" refString="Fricke, R, 1999. Fishes of the Mascarene Islands (Reunion, Mauritius, Rodriguez). An annotated checklist with descriptions of new species. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein, i-viii + 1-759." title="Fishes of the Mascarene Islands (Reunion, Mauritius, Rodriguez). An annotated checklist with descriptions of new species. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein, i-viii + 1 - 759." year="1999">Fricke 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fricke, R" journalOrPublisher="FishTaxa: Journal of Fish Taxonomy" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="1 - 432" refId="B8" refString="Fricke, R, Mahafina, J, Behivoke, F, Jaonalison, H, Leopold, M, Ponton, D, 2018. Annotated checklist of the fishes of Madagascar, southwestern Indian Ocean, with 158 new records. FishTaxa: Journal of Fish Taxonomy 3 (1): 1 - 432" title="Annotated checklist of the fishes of Madagascar, southwestern Indian Ocean, with 158 new records." volume="3" year="2018">Fricke et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The current findings represent a range extension of ca. 700 km to the northeast of the closest previously known region (Maldives), and the first record of this species from India. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Valenciennes" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Actinopterygii" family="Labridae" genus="Oxycheilinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oxycheilinus arenatus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Oxycheilinus arenatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in the Indo-West Pacific and was probably previously overlooked in Indian waters. Apparently, the species is very rare in India.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
This species is found in caves of steep outer reef drop-offs from 25 to at least 46 m with rich invertebrate growth such as large gorgonians or soft corals (
<bibRefCitation author="Froese, R" journalOrPublisher="FishTaxa: Journal of Fish Taxonomy" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" publicationUrl="https://www.fishbase.se/search.php" refId="B11" refString="Froese, R, Pauly, D, 2022. (2022) FishBase. [Version 02/2022] https://www.fishbase.se/search.php" title="(2022) FishBase. [Version 02 / 2022]" url="https://www.fishbase.se/search.php" year="2022">Froese and Pauly 2022</bibRefCitation>
). It is naturally rare and has been rarely documented due to its cryptic occurrence in deep reefs. The lower extent of the depth distribution range is unknown. The collecting depth of the Indian specimens below 40 m well agrees with the previously known depth range.
</paragraph>
